data.content:
Here's a complete migration analysis and rewrite for .NET 8.

## Problems in the Original Code

| Issue | Severity | Details |
|-------|----------|--------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | 🔴 **Breaks** | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 5+ (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | 🟡 **Obsolete** | Deprecated SYSLIB0046; throws in .NET 9+. Only wakes `WaitSleepJoin` state |
| Race condition | 🟡 **Bug** | Multiple `Enqueue` calls → only one `Dequeue` per `WaitOne/Reset` cycle (items lost) |
| No graceful shutdown | 🟡 **Design** | No cooperative signal to exit `while(true)` — relies on forced termination |

## Pattern Classification (per skill)

| Call site | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `_thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `_thread.Interrupt()` | Blocking call interruption | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with `token.WaitHandle` |
| `_newEvent.WaitOne()` | Blocking call | `WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle })` |
| `while (true)` | Infinite loop | `while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _task;

    public void Start()
    {
        _task = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Graceful shutdown — expected
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel closed.");
    }

    public async Task StopAsync(TimeSpan? timeout = null)
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();              // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(timeout ?? TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // enforce timeout
        if (_task is not null)
            await _task;                         // wait for drain
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

### Why `Channel<T>`?

- **Eliminates the race condition** — the original `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` lost items when multiple `Enqueue` calls fired before one `Dequeue`. `Channel<T>` is a thread-safe producer/consumer queue with built-in signaling.
- **No manual locking** — `_lock`, `ManualResetEvent`, and `Queue` are all replaced by one primitive.
- **Cooperative cancellation** — `ReadAllAsync(token)` responds to the `CancellationToken`, replacing both `Thread.Interrupt()` and `Thread.Abort()`.

### If you must stay synchronous (no async)

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };

        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wake on either new-event OR cancellation
            int signaled = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (signaled == 1) break; // cancellation

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes the race condition)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();                  // wakes WaitAny immediately
        _thread?.Join(5000);            // wait for clean exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback — cooperative cancellation is sufficient
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();
        _cts.Dispose();
        _newEvent.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* ... */ }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | How this migration avoids it |
|---------|------------------------------|
| `CancellationToken` not checked in loop | `ReadAllAsync(token)` / `WaitAny` checks every iteration |
| Token not interrupting blocking wait | `WaitHandle.WaitAny` includes `token.WaitHandle` — no stuck threads |
| `CancellationTokenSource` leaked | `IDisposable` implemented, `_cts.Dispose()` called |
| `OperationCanceledException` swallowed silently | Caught only `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` — unexpected exceptions propagate |
| No fallback for `Thread.Abort` | Not needed — cooperative cancellation guarantees the loop exits at the next checkpoint |

The **`Channel<T>` version is strongly recommended** — it's simpler, fixes the race condition, and is the idiomatic .NET 8 pattern for producer/consumer queues.
